p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q105 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> As the finance man, can you tell us why the accounts are so late?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Driver</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: Because we had an issue with the impairment of Universal Credit, which we have been talking about and—</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> So, it was down to write-off.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Driver</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: There was an issue of significant, we believe, public interest in getting that right before we published our accounts.  But when we sat with the Public Accounts Committee in September, we had identified that we felt that the impairment was going to be £34.4 million and, beyond that, we felt there was some uncertainty about the accounts and we might have to impair something like an additional £12.5 million.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size: