s New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Driver</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: Our management accounts will show an impairment of £40.1 million for Universal Credit.  We have not written down or amortised our asset beyond that, because it only went into live running on 29 April, so, in our accounts for 2013-14, we will show how much of that asset is written down in those accounts.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mr Duncan Smith</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: As you would with any capital programme.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q109 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Thank you.  And the accounts will be published tomorrow.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Driver</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: They will.  They will be laid with Parliament tomorrow, so both the Permanent Secretary and the C&amp;AG have signed the accounts.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q110 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Minister, there has been a lot of debate about the timetable for Universal Credit.  There has been concern that maybe it was going too fast, and then it was going too slow.  Have you, at any time, issued a ministerial direction to the Department?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mr Duncan Smith</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: On what?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> On the timetabling.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mr Duncan Smith</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: I have actually issued no ministerial directions to the Department on anything, but certainly not on timing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q111 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Did the Permanent Secretary ever request a ministerial direction?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mr Duncan Smith</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: No.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q112 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> There will be no ministerial directions published along with the accounts tomorrow.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mr Duncan Smith</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: None whatsoever.  At the PAC hearing, it was made quite clear that Ministers were completely sanguine about timings on this.  We agreed with the original proposals put forward and laid out, but at no stage have we ever sought to accelerate or change those timings arbitrarily, at any stage.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Driver</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: It would be an accounting requirement for us to declare any directions, and there are none.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q113 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> We have waited so long for these accounts; I just wondered if we were going to get any more surprises.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mr Duncan Smith</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: Do not worry.  There are no surprises; nothing like that.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q114 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Mr Shiplee, you are in charge now, as I see it.  There are two different types of IT project: there is agile and waterfall.  Could you explain the difference?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Howard Shiplee</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: I thought I had done that before, but certainly.  waterfall, as I have said, is something whereby we would start off with a very clear specification.  You write down exactly what you want and what you believe is going to work, and then you develop it and you test it.  The agile system, for software development, is different.  What it says is that you learn as you go, you make mistakes as you go and you do it all in a very iterative process.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q115 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> So this project is an agile project.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Howard Shiplee</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: The work that we are doing now in terms of the digital part of the work is very much agile.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q116 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Only that part of the work.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Howard Shiplee</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: Yes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q117 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> One of the criticisms of Government Departments and local authorities as well is that they find it hard to be an intelligent client, because, often, the people you are buying IT from or who are selling you solutions are more savvy than, maybe, civil servants.  Do you think that the DWP is now an intelligent client?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Howard Shiplee</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: Yes, I do, first of all because, in terms of the digital work, we are doing that in-house.  I am very grateful to Government Digital Services, who came in after the David Pitchford reviews and commenced the process of the digital design processes.  The plan there was that we would, ultimately, as a Department, take that over.  They helped to get us started and that is now happening.  With the arrival of our DG for Digital Change, he is now taking a very clear lead in that work, and we are actively bringing in our own people, who will start to replace the GDS people, so we are doing it ourselves.  That is exactly the right thing to do, because of the way the iterative process works, testing it on claimants in small numbers and in focus groups, and that has proved to be very effective in terms of the proof of concept.  Everyone who has seen the proof of concept—and I think your Committee has seen some of it—has agreed that this looks like the way to go.  Of course, the proof of concept is the start and there is a lot more work to do thereafter.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q118 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> This is a question you may have answered earlier on, but just to clarify for me, has the new migration timetable not yet been subjected to a formal business review.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Howard Shiplee</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: The business case is due for presentation to HMT in the early part of next year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q119 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Teresa Pearce:</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt"> Do you know when?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Howard Shiplee</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: From memory, March.  Mike, you might be able to help.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Driver</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: It is earlier than that.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mr Duncan Smith</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: It is earlier than that, I think.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Mike Driver</span><span style="font-family:Garamond; font-size:12pt">: I think we had had some discussions with the Treasury about trying to share the bus